title: Supreme Court blow to Trump’s tariffs could trigger $247 billion in refunds
description: The US Supreme Court's ruling that many of President Donald Trump's tariffs are illegal will likely lead to billions of dollars in refunds.   It's estimated as much as 247 billion dollars AUD could be sought by importers for the tariffs already paid.  US President Donald Trump declared the Supreme Court's ruling as ‘deeply disappointing.  “I’m ashamed of certain members of the court,” Mr Trump said  “It’s my opinion that the court has been swayed by foreign interest.”

title: Seven dead after a tour bus plunged into Lake Baikal in Russia's Siberia
description: Seven people have died after a tour bus plunged into the water in Lake Baikal in Russia's Siberia.  The bus was carrying eight Chinese tourists when the ice broke as it crossed the frozen lake on Friday.   The region's prosecutor's office has opened a criminal case over the incident.   Lake Baikal is the world's deepest freshwater lake and is a popular tourist destination.

title: Mexico's Navy has seized a submarine carrying four tons of cocaine
description: Mexico's Navy has seized a submarine carrying four tons of cocaine in the Pacific Ocean.  The operation was undertaken with intelligence shared by the US Northern Command.    Mexican authorities claim the latest seizure has brought the total amount of drugs confiscated in a week to 10 tonnes.  Three people were arrested during the operation.

title: $21 billion in unclaimed super sitting in 7.3 million forgotten accounts
description: The federal government warns millions of Australians are missing out on a fraction of their superannuation.  Data suggests there is more than 21 billion dollars in unclaimed super earnings that are sitting in forgotten accounts.    There are approximately 7.3 million Australian accounts that have unclaimed superannuation.    Assistant Treasurer Daniel Mulino says it is possible for people to get those funds back.   People can find any of their unclaimed superannuation through multiple channels, including checking the ATO website.

title: Latest Andrew drama has ‘taken some of the heat’ off of ‘embattled’ Keir Starmer
description: Spiked Online Editor Tom Slater claims Andrew Mounbatten-Windsor’s arrest has “taken some of the heat off” of UK Prime Minister Keir Starmer.   “I think it’s taken some of the heat off of the prime minister,” Mr Slater told Sky News host Caleb Bond.   “It was only a week or so ago that it felt like one of the main kinds of casualties of this latest round of the Epstein files being released was going to be Keir Starmer’s government.”

title: Keir Starmer sees Andrew’s arrest as ‘welcome air’ taking pressure off of his situation
description: Sky News host Caleb Bond thinks UK Prime Minister Keir Starmer must see Andrew Mountbatten-Windsor’s arrest as some “welcome air”.   “Keir Starmer in some way must be feeling a bit relieved,” Mr Bond said.  “Because of course, all the heat when it came to the Epstein files until now … had been on him and his appointment of Lord Peter Mandelson.  “Now you suddenly have a much bigger story on the scene.”

title: Sinister surveillance fears grow after Super Bowl spotlight on AI doorbells
description: Privacy worries are growing over video surveillance and artificial intelligence after an Amazon Ring doorbell advertisement featured in the recent Super Bowl.    The commercial highlighted a feature designed to help locate and identify lost pets, demonstrating how the smart doorbell can analyse footage and recognise specific animals.   While marketed as a helpful innovation for families, the advancement has sparked unease among privacy advocates and tech experts.  Critics warn that technology capable of identifying pets today could potentially be adapted to recognise people tomorrow, raising questions about facial recognition, data storage and how footage may be accessed or shared.   Others have questioned how long video data is retained, who ultimately controls it, and whether law enforcement or third parties could seek access.  The Super Bowl showcase served as a reminder of how quickly AI-driven surveillance is becoming embedded in everyday life and how blurred the line between helpful and intrusive technology may become.

title: Three killed as US strike obliterates alleged narco boat
description: Three people have been killed after the US Military struck an alleged drug-carrying vessel in the Pacific Ocean.  US Southern Command has posted a video on social media showing a boat floating in the water before bursting into flames.   It claims the vessel was engaged in narco-trafficking operations.

title: ‘Scared of the ballet box’: Keir Starmer tried to cancel elections for 4.5 million voters
description: UK Prime Minister Keir Starmer cancelled local elections for 4.5 million voters.  “UK Prime Minister Keir Starmer has literally tried to cancel democracy,” Ms De Giorgio said.   “He is so scared of his own shadow and so scared of the ballet box that he cancelled citizens’ rights.”

title: ‘Someone needs to be dismissed’: IOC president threatens staff after blindsiding questions
description: Tensions flared at the closing news conference of the Winter Games in Italy as IOC President Kristy Coventry publicly rebuked members of her own communications team.  Pressed on reports that Germany is hesitant to pursue hosting the 2036 Olympic Games, Ms Coventry said she was unaware of the story and openly expressed frustration that it had not been brought to her attention.  Moments later, she faced questions about a New York Times investigation alleging the IOC had been aware that the chair of Russia’s anti-doping agency was directly involved in widespread doping linked to the Sochi Games.   Again, Ms Coventry said she had not been briefed and signalled her anger at the staff.  “I’m really looking at my team, and maybe someone needs to be dismissed because I’m not aware of that either,” Ms Coventry said.

title: ‘Definitely lifeforms’: Trump to release government files after Obama says aliens are real
description: Sky News contributor Joe Hildebrand pokes fun at US President Donald Trump for claiming he will release government files on Aliens after former US president Barack Obama claimed aliens are real.  “When he [Obama] was asked are there aliens, he said yes,” Mr Hildebrand told Sky News host Steve Price.  “Statistically speaking, there absolutely 100 per cent definitely are lifeforms on other planets.”

title: 150-year homecoming as giant tortoises return to Floreana Island
description: Giant tortoises have returned to Ecuador’s Floreana Island in a landmark conservation milestone more than 150 years in the making.  In the first phase of a broader rewilding effort, 158 juvenile tortoises were released, with plans to introduce up to 700 in total to help restore the species to its former habitat.  Floreana, part of the Galapagos Islands, was once home to around 20,000 giant tortoises before they were driven to extinction there.  Conservationists hope the new arrivals will re-establish a thriving population, one that could soon outnumber the island’s roughly 200 human residents.

title: ‘Washed up’ Jimmy Kimmel to host exclusive $25k fundraiser
description: New York Post Editor-at-Large Kelly Jane Torrance criticises Late Night host Jimmy Kimmel as it is announced he will headline pricy fundraiser where guests have to pay $25 thousand USD per ticket.  “It is really quite funny that you have to pay 25K just to get in the door,” Ms Torrance told Sky News host James Morrow.  “Jimmy Kimmel, the guy’s kind of washed up; his ratings are down.”

title: Work-from-home war: Vic Premier and Lord Mayor clash in public showdown
description: A debate over Victoria’s work-from-home plans has sparked a war of words between Premier Jacinta Allan and Melbourne’s Lord Mayor Nick Reece.  Lord Mayor Nick Reece has warned the Allan government over its proposed work-from-home reforms, saying they could derail the state's post-pandemic recovery.  Mr Reece wrote a letter to the Premier claiming that 'the right to work from home is not good'.  Premier Jacinta Allan then accused him of attempting to 'drag her words backwards'.

title: PM Keir Starmer forced into humiliating U-turn after trying to cancel elections
description: GB News host Alex Armstrong criticises Prime Minister Keir Starmer, who was forced into a humiliating backdown after attempting to cancel local elections.  “The Prime Minister was forced into a humiliating U-turn on cancelling local elections across the United Kingdom,” Mr Armstrong told Sky News host Danica De Giorgio.  “The question was always asked is this all happening because Labour are terrified of Reform UK.  “The government had to concede to Reform UK.”
